node.text:
SN8 had a (mostly) successful hop test yesterday, with SpaceX just falling short at the last hurdle. Elon Musk was still keen to convey the message that the test flight was still largely successful, tweeting out: “Mars here we come!” Directly after the explosion. 

Congratulations to the entire SpaceX team for this huge accomplishment! Here’s to SN9!

node.text:
Rate this photo of Endeavour from 1-10!🛸 

This picture is from STS-118, the first flight of Space Shuttle Endeavour since STS-113 in 2002. The mission's purpose was to resupply the International Space Station. 

STS-118 lasted for just under 13 days, with the crew of 7 landing back at the Kennedy Space Center on Tuesday the 12th of August, 2007. 

- 
Follow @rocketreport for the latest in space 🚀

node.text:
Some AMAZING shots of Earth’s sister planet, Venus. 📸 

The first shot is a composite image from Venera-13, a Soviet lander sent on a one-way mission to the planet back in 1981. This was one of the few photos taken by Venera-13, as the lander only functioned for around 2 hours (actually around 4x longer than expected) due to the harsh climate of Venus. The planet hosts average temperatures of 457 °C and a pressure of 89 Earth atmospheres! So, not the nicest vacation spot 😬 

In order, credit for these images goes to Roscosmos, JAXA and NASA. 📸 

I found these images on @spacetroves ’ Instagram page. Check them out for some awesome space pics! 

Follow @rocketreport for the latest in space 🚀

A launch could be expected as early late August - early September providing everything goes to plan.

node.text:
Space Shuttle Enterprise being lowered into Marshall's Dynamic Test Stand for a vibration test! 

Enterprise was a test-module built for NASA to perform atmospheric test flights after being launched from a modified Boeing 747.

It was constructed without engines or a functional heat shield, meaning it was incapable or orbital space flight, despite initial aspirations of reforming the frame for orbital fight.

node.text:
Incredible exhaust-shot of a Proton-M launch from July 2020!

This rocket uses a hypergolic propellant combination, in which the fluids spontaneously ignite upon contact with one another. A big advantage of using hypergolic propellants is that, unlike LOX/LH, (Liquid Oxygen/Liquid Hydrogen, a popular fuel combo used on many launch systems, including the Space Shuttle) they can be stored as liquids at room temperature. 

Engines that are powered by them are also able ignite repeatedly! This makes a great combination for spacecraft that need multiple restarts of an engine to be able to make course corrections, or change an orbital path somewhat spontaneously (for whatever reason) 

Many conventional engines are limited to minimal engine restarts, which means missions must be planned with much more scrutiny. 

Follow @rocketreport for more like this! 🚀

node.text:
Believe it or not, this space suit is completely empty! 

This Russian satellite, dubbed 'SuitSat', began its orbit around Earth after it was deployed outside of the ISS by the crew members of Expedition 12 during an EVA on the 3rd of February, 2006. 

The suit encasing the satellite technology was the Russian Orlan spacesuit, and was stuffed with batteries, sensors and a radio transmitter, which faintly transmitted recorded voices of school children to amateur radio operators worldwide (creepy!!!)

The suit disintegrated a few weeks later upon atmospheric re-entry. 

Follow @rocketreport for more!

node.text:
Here are some cool shots from back when the Space Shuttle made routine trips to the Russian Mir space station! 

Mir operated in low Earth orbit, about 50 kilometres lower than the ISS orbits today. In turn, this provided some super interesting views of Earth! 

Mir made history as the first-ever modular space station and was assembled in orbit between the years of 1986 & 1996.

In all, the Space Shuttle was involved in 11 flights to Mir, providing some excellent pictures of the station orbiting our planet 🌏

All images taken from NASA’s image archives, the website in question is images.nasa.gov

Follow @rocketreport for the latest in space 🚀
